A .NET Temporal workflow uses `Workflow.CurrentDetails` to emit rich Markdown progress updates throughout a long-running order fulfillment process. The team also attaches `Summary` strings (up to 200 bytes) to each Activity invocation and to `Workflow.DelayWithOptionsAsync` timer steps. During a post-incident review, engineers discover that after a Worker crash and replay, the UI shows stale `CurrentDetails` from before the crash, even though the Workflow eventually completed correctly. Which of the following best explains the interaction between Workflow replay, event history, and the `CurrentDetails` / `Summary` metadata fields that caused this observation?

```csharp
[WorkflowRun]
public async Task<string> RunAsync(string orderId)
{
    Workflow.CurrentDetails = $"Starting order {orderId}";
    var result = await Workflow.ExecuteActivityAsync(
        (OrderActivities act) => act.ReserveInventoryAsync(orderId),
        new ActivityOptions
        {
            StartToCloseTimeout = TimeSpan.FromMinutes(5),
            Summary = "Reserving inventory"
        });
    Workflow.CurrentDetails = $"Inventory reserved, processing payment";
    await Workflow.DelayWithOptionsAsync(
        new DelayOptions(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30)) { Summary = "Payment gateway delay" });
    Workflow.CurrentDetails = $"Order {orderId} complete";
    return result;
}
```

An engineering team starts a high-volume batch Workflow using the .NET SDK and sets both `StaticSummary` and `StaticDetails` in `WorkflowOptions`. Six months later they add per-Activity `Summary` metadata and update `Workflow.CurrentDetails` inside the Workflow. A compliance team then queries the Temporal Web UI and notices that several completed Workflows — all finished before the code change — show `StaticSummary` and `StaticDetails` correctly, but display no Activity-level summaries and show only the initial `CurrentDetails` value (set in the very first workflow task). Which combination of Temporal architectural behaviors best explains this observation?

```csharp
var handle = await client.StartWorkflowAsync(
    (BatchWorkflow wf) => wf.RunAsync(batchId),
    new WorkflowOptions
    {
        Id = $"batch-{batchId}",
        TaskQueue = "batch-queue",
        StaticSummary = $"Batch job {batchId}",
        StaticDetails = "Nightly ETL pipeline — compliance tier"
    });
```
